##pie chart in pie(x,labels, radius, main, col, clockwise)

x= vector lables = discription to the vectors radius = -1 to +1 main = title of chart col= color for chart colockwise = clockwise and anticlockwise T/F

#eg
x= c(20,15,25,30,10)

labels= c("sugu","rosy","sixer","corona","covid")

#eg1

##saving a graph/diagram 1) x= c(20,15,25,30,10)…………………………data for graph

labels= c(“sugu”,“rosy”,“sixer”,“corona”,“covid”)

  1. png(file=“filename.png”)…………….chart file name

  2. pie(x,labels, radius = 1,main = “hostel”,col=rainbow (5), colockwise = F)

  3. dev.off() …………..for svaing the file ``

x= c(20,15,25,30,10)
labels= c("sugu","rosy","sixer","corona","covid")
png(file= "hostel.png")
pie (x,labels, radius = 1,main = "hostel", col=rainbow (5))

dev.off()
## png 
##   2

#percentage pie

piepercent=round(100*x/sum(x),1)
pie(x,labels=piepercent, radius = 1,main = "hostel", col=rainbow(length(x)))
legend("topright", c("sugu","rosy","sixer","corona","covid"), cex=0.5, fill=rainbow(length(x)))

#Bar diagaram barplot(H,xlab,ylab,main,names.arg, col) H-data xlab- x axis label ylab- y axis label main - chart title names.arg- vecor containing names for each bar col- color for bar

png(file="bar.png")
H=c(8,12,9,11,6)
label= c("S1","S2","S3","S4","S5")

dev.off()

Histogram

hist(V,main=,xlab=,xlim=,ylim=,breaks=,col=, border=)

v- vector data main - title of diagram xlab- labels of x axis xlim- limt of x ylim- limt of y breaks= bar numbers or width of bar

v=c(2,5,8,11,15,18,22,26,30,34,39)

hist(v,main = "Salinity",xlab = "locations", col= "yellow",breaks = 8, border="black")

## xlim & ylim in histogram

v=c(2,5,8,11,15,18,22,26,30,34,39)
png(file="histogram.png")
hist(v,main = "Salinity",xlab = "locations",xlim=c(0,40), ylim= c(0,3), col= "yellow",breaks = 8, border="black")
dev.off()

##Line graph plot(v,type,col,xlab,ylab) v- data vector type- “p” only points, “l” only lines, “o” both lines and ponits

xlab- labels of x axis ylab- lables for y axis col - colors

v=as.integer(c(2.2,2.8, 3.5,3.9, 4.2))
plot(v,type="p",xlab="concentration",ylab = "ABS",col="red",main = "STD")

plot(v,type="o",xlab="ABS",ylab = "concentration",col="red",main = "STD")

plot(v,type="l",xlab="ABS",ylab = "concentration",col= "red",main = "STD")

#multiple plot

v=as.integer(c(2.2,2.8, 3.5,3.9, 4.2))
p=as.integer(c(2.0,2.1, 2.8,3.2, 3.8))
q=as.integer(c(2.4,2.6, 3.2,3.6, 3.9))

plot(v,type="o",xlab="concentration",ylab = "ABS",col="red",main = "STD")
lines(p,type="o",col="blue")
lines(q,type="o",col="green")

# xlim and ylim not allowed here
v=as.integer(c(2.2,2.8, 3.5,3.9, 4.2))
p=as.integer(c(2.0,2.1, 2.8,3.2, 3.8))
q=as.integer(c(2.4,2.6, 3.2,3.6, 3.9))
png(file="linegraph.png")
plot(v,type="o",xlab="concentration",ylab = "ABS",col="red",main = "STD")
lines(p,type="o",col="blue")
lines(q,type="o",col="green")
dev.off()

### Barplot with multiple groups

df2 <- data.frame(supp=rep(c("VC", "OJ"), each=3),
                dose=rep(c("D0.5", "D1", "D2"),2),
                len=c(6.8, 15, 33, 4.2, 10, 29.5))
head(df2)
##   supp dose  len
## 1   VC D0.5  6.8
## 2   VC   D1 15.0
## 3   VC   D2 33.0
## 4   OJ D0.5  4.2
## 5   OJ   D1 10.0
## 6   OJ   D2 29.5
ggplot(data=df2, aes(x=dose, y=len, fill=supp)) +
  geom_bar(stat="identity") +
  theme_light()

ggplot(data=df2, aes(x=dose, y=len, fill=supp)) +
geom_bar(stat="identity", position = position_dodge() )+
  theme_minimal()
